<TITLE> More aid pours in </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 22 (bdnews24.com)  India has donated relief materials worth Tk 5.2 crore for Sidr survivors. Two Indian aircraft arrived Thursday and Friday loaded with donations. A third aircraft is likely to reach Dhaka Saturday. The whole Indian relief package worth Tk 5.2 crore includes 39.5 tonnes of ready-to-eat food packets, 0.5 tonnes of water purification tablets, 1 tonne of medicines, 400 tents and 10,000 blankets, said a statement of the Indian High Commission in Dhaka. The 1.9 kilogram food packets contain staples including rice, flour, pulses, chapati , milk, tea, sugar, hexamine tablets and a small cooker. Foreign adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury Thursday met Indian foreign minister Pranab Mukherjee in the Ugandan capital Kampala on the sidelines of the Commonwealth summit. Mukherjee assured Iftekhar of all possible help from India with both immediate relief and thereafter. The Chinese government Thursday offered 1,000 tonnes of rice, 500 tonnes of wheat flour and 100 tonnes of edible oil in aid. China had earlier pledged $1 million for the cyclone-hit people. The government of Sri Lanka also announced Thursday a donation of $25,000 to the Chief Adviser's Relief Fund, according to a foreign ministry press release. Pakistan has sent two military aircrafts to Bangladesh carrying supplies for a 30-bed mobile hospital, which were expected to arrive Friday in the southern district of Barisal, says a press release of the government's Press Information Department. bdnews24
